      Audit
   =20
 =20

Often, if you are marketing an investment, it helps to have your thing vali=
dated by some trusted third party. If you=E2=80=99ve got a company and you =
want investors, it=E2=80=99s good to send them financial statements that ha=
ve been audited by a well-known accounting firm. If you=E2=80=99re selling =
bonds, it=E2=80=99s good to have a high credit rating from a recognized rat=
ings firm. If you=E2=80=99re a software company, it is good to have a secur=
ity audit from a reputable firm.
If you are running a scam, all of=C2=A0this is also true, maybe even more s=
o: If you=E2=80=99re selling a fake thing, it is very helpful for you to sa=
y =E2=80=9Cthis thing has been certified by a trusted third party.=E2=80=9D=
 But of course that is hard, because the reason the trusted third parties a=
re trusted is because they are in the business of=C2=A0not=C2=A0certifying =
scams, so they are unlikely to certify you.
There are ways, of course. Perhaps if you are clever you can deceive the au=
ditors into certifying your financial statements. Perhaps you can bribe the=
m. Perhaps you can hire (or set up) some shady fake auditor and give it a t=
rusted-sounding name. Maybe your financial statements were audited by KMPG =
and your bonds are rated AAA by Moodie=E2=80=99s Investors Service.=C2=A0
An approach that I had not really thought of is:
=09Go to a real, well-regarded, trusted auditing firm.=09Ask them to audit =
your thing.=09They conduct the audit and send you back a letter being like =
=E2=80=9Cno, see, this is actually a=C2=A0scam.=E2=80=9D=09You go around to=
 investors saying =E2=80=9Cyou can trust us because we were audited by the =
good firm!=E2=80=9D=09The investors are like =E2=80=9Cah well anyone audite=
d by that firm must be fine=E2=80=9D and give you their money.

Technically, I think, =E2=80=9Cwe were audited by X=E2=80=9D just means tha=
t they=C2=A0did=C2=A0the audited, not that you=C2=A0passed.=C2=A0It=E2=80=
=99s maybe=C2=A0true? And yet misleading? Also seems not that helpful: A so=
phisticated investor would probably say =E2=80=9Cah right let=E2=80=99s see=
 the audit report,=E2=80=9D while an unsophisticated one probably wouldn=E2=
=80=99t care, or recognize the auditing firm=E2=80=99s name. Still. It help=
s with the patter; it gives things the ring of truth.
Anyway here=E2=80=99s a  Colorado Securities Commission fraud case against =
a pastor named Eli Regalado and his wife Kaitlyn, who started a crypto thin=
g called INDXcoin, and a crypto exchange called Kingdom Wealth Exchange to =
trade it. Standard stuff, you know, God told them to sell crypto, etc.:

According to the complaint filed by the Colorado Attorney General=E2=80=99s=
 Office, investigators from the Colorado Division of Securities found that =
from June 2022 to April 2023, INDXcoin raised nearly $3.2 million from more=
 than 300 individuals. The complaint alleges that Regalado targeted Christi=
an communities in Denver and claimed that God told him directly that invest=
ors would become wealthy if they put money into INDXcoin. ...
The Regalados allegedly continued to promote the INDXcoin as a low risk, hi=
gh profit investment.
The complaint alleges that in reality, the INDXcoin was illiquid and practi=
cally worthless; investors lost millions; and Defendants dissipated investo=
r funds to support their lavish lifestyle.

Again, the appeal to a trusted third-party authority (God). Plus some bizar=
re claims about the mechanics of the crypto thing; from  the complaint:
The =E2=80=9CINDXcoin, as described by Defendants in the Whitepaper, is pur=
portedly an =E2=80=9Cindex-based cryptocurrency that tracks and indexes the=
 value of the top one hundred cryptocurrencies (ranked by market cap) throu=
gh an AI-based data procurement mechanism sourced from multiple data points=
 to ensure accuracy.=E2=80=9D
Nooo.
  [1]

Defendants persuaded investors that the INDXcoin was uniquely situated to p=
rovide its holders with big returns. Defendants explained that INDXcoin was=
 designed to be =E2=80=9Ca less volatile and risky coin to hold...with less=
 exposure to the risks associated with single coin offerings.=E2=80=9D Defe=
ndants said INDXcoin was =E2=80=9Cimmune to investors =E2=80=98pumping and =
dumping=E2=80=99 cryptocurrency through a coordinated liquidation event,=E2=
=80=9D as the value of the INDXcoin was pegged to =E2=80=9Cthe overall mome=
ntum of the crypto market.=E2=80=9D Defendants=E2=80=99 future plans would =
only provide more assurance to coin holders, acting to =E2=80=9Csolidify IN=
DXcoin=E2=80=99s global value, acting as the first line of defense against =
exchange-specific price volatility if a large portfolio holding INDXcoin is=
 liquidated on an exchange.=E2=80=9D
Whatever. But for some reason they decided to go to a crypto=C2=A0auditing =
firm called Hacken,  whose website tells me that they have done smart contr=
act audits for crypto things including Binance. =E2=80=9CDefendants touted =
the safety of INDXcoin and the KWE by telling investors that the coin and t=
he exchange had undergone a rigorous audit.=E2=80=9D How=E2=80=99d the audi=
t go?

The auditor, Hacken, told Defendants their products=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Csecur=
ity score=E2=80=9D was zero out of ten. Additionally, wrote Hacken, =E2=80=
=9C[c]onsidering all metrics, the total score of the report is 0 out of 10.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
According to the Hacken report, =E2=80=9C[w]hen proof-of-stake mining is en=
abled, value of reward in coinbase is not validated which allows to generat=
e any number of new coins...In practice, it allows to generate an infinite =
number of new coins.=E2=80=9D ...
To the extent that Hacken could evaluate Defendants=E2=80=99 code, Hacken h=
ighlighted that the code submitted by Defendants contained changes that =E2=
=80=9Cdid not=C2=A0align with the standards upheld by Bitcoin Core,=E2=80=
=9D and contained transcription errors that lead to =E2=80=9Cnumerous criti=
cal issues.=E2=80=9D

Seems bad! And yet also good marketing:

However, upon receiving the Hacken Report, Defendants posted in the KWE Com=
