   =20
      Elsewhere in third-party audits
   =20
 =20

Here is a=C2=A0 report from Moody=E2=80=99s about shell companies. =E2=80=
=9CShell company=E2=80=9D is a somewhat vague term, referring to =E2=80=9Cc=
orporations without significant business assets or operations,=E2=80=9D in =
Moody=E2=80=99s words. There is in general nothing particularly nefarious a=
bout having some spare corporations lying around, to optimize liability or =
ownership or debt subordination or jurisdiction or, yes, fine, of course, t=
axes. (When I was a young mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer I would occasiona=
lly form a bunch of Delaware=C2=A0shell companies for future use doing merg=
ers, and I always got a tiny Bond-villainish thrill from putting my name on=
 them.) But, says Moody=E2=80=99s, =E2=80=9Cthese legal instruments can be =
abused by bad actors to launder money gained through illicit activities, su=
ch as trafficking and environmental crime. They can create a mask for sanct=
ioned individuals to disguise their business ownership, and they can hide f=
inancial crimes, such as tax evasion, fraud, and bribery.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
So Moody=E2=80=99s analyzed a database of =E2=80=9Cmore than 472 million co=
mpanies=E2=80=9D to identify red flags for when a company might be a=C2=A0b=
ad=C2=A0shell company, or a shell company anyway?=C2=A0
Moody=E2=80=99s industry practitioners say that a company that raises two o=
r more flags may be at a heightened risk of being a shell company, that is =
to say, a corporation without active business operations or significant ass=
ets.=C2=A0The indication that an entity is a shell company gives customers =
the ability to further investigate whether the company is potentially being=
 used for illicit activities.
Red flags include =E2=80=9Cmass registration=E2=80=9D (if someone forms 100=
 companies on the same day, they=E2=80=99re probably shells), =E2=80=9Cjuri=
sdictional risk=E2=80=9D (Panama), =E2=80=9Cfinancial anomalies=E2=80=9D (=
=E2=80=9Ca China-based textiles and clothing manufacturer reported more tha=
n $2 billion in revenue in 2019 =E2=80=94 and only one employee=E2=80=9D), =
=E2=80=9Cdormancy,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccircular ownership=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Catypical directorships=E2=80=9D (too many directors at a company, =
or one director being on too many boards).=C2=A0And: =E2=80=9CBy sector, th=
e business services sector raises the most flags with approximately 3.6 mil=
lion total,=E2=80=9D which sounds right; if you=E2=80=99re going to set up =
a fake company it will probably be in the =E2=80=9Cbusiness services=E2=80=
=9D sector rather than, like, biotech. (=E2=80=9CWholesale=E2=80=9D comes i=
n second.)
But the best red flag is director age. Directors of big public companies te=
nd to be serious professionals chosen for their expertise and judgment, but=
 directors of shell companies are often warm bodies chosen for their willin=
gness to sign their names to=C2=A0documents. (Again, as a young mergers-and=
-acquisitions lawyer, I probably made myself a director of a few merger sub=
s.) Directors of=C2=A0shady=C2=A0shell companies, then, have some propensit=
y to be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0cold bodies? People who signed fake names to documen=
ts?=C2=A0

The average age of registered company directors in Moody=E2=80=99s database=
 is 52 years. A director is typically appointed by the company=E2=80=99s sh=
areholders or board of directors, and their name is listed on the public re=
gister of the company. In many jurisdictions, minors under the age of 18 ar=
en=E2=80=99t eligible to be directors.
Moody=E2=80=99s tool has revealed thousands of directors who are as young a=
s zero or older than the world=E2=80=99s longest-living person on record. O=
ne listed director =E2=80=94 at 943 years old =E2=80=94 would have been bor=
n in the 11th century. This director is allegedly a minority shareholder an=
d beneficial owner of a Belgium-based business services firm that incorpora=
ted in 2018.

Har har har but also there are allegedly more than 30,000 shell company dir=
ectors who are older than 100? Seems high.

