      Workplace excellence
   =20
 =20

If you are a big bank and you want your employees to work from the office t=
hree days a week, and some of your employees don=E2=80=99t do that, it seem=
s pretty reasonable to send those employees a letter=C2=A0saying =E2=80=9Co=
ur policies require you to be in the office at least three days a week, you=
 have not met that requirement, and if you keep it up you might get fired.=
=E2=80=9D A lot of companies, understandably, have some sort of work-from-t=
he-office policy, and if you have that policy, you will probably need an en=
forcement mechanism, warnings of consequences, records of warnings of conse=
quences, etc., the whole apparatus of human resources formality.
Still  the language=C2=A0here just sounds like it was generated by an artif=
icial intelligence set to =E2=80=9Cevil=E2=80=9D:

Bank of America has sent =E2=80=9Cletters of education=E2=80=9D to employee=
s who have not been showing up at the office, warning them of disciplinary =
action, in the latest move from a large company to push staff back to the w=
orkplace.
One of the messages said its recipient had failed to meet the bank=E2=80=99=
s =E2=80=9CWorkplace Excellence Guidelines=E2=80=9D for work location =E2=
=80=9Cdespite requests and reminders to do so=E2=80=9D.
=E2=80=9CFailure to follow the workplace excellence expectations applicable=
 to your role within two weeks of the date of this notification may result =
in further disciplinary action,=E2=80=9D according to the text of the lette=
r that a BofA employee posted online.

You can say =E2=80=9Cshowing up at the office=E2=80=9D instead of =E2=80=9C=
workplace excellence expectations=E2=80=9D! That=E2=80=99s clearer and less=
, like, dystopian. You can call it a =E2=80=9Cwarning=E2=80=9D instead of a=
 =E2=80=9Cletter of education.=E2=80=9D Why does everyone have to be so=C2=
=A0weird=C2=A0about return-to-office.

