<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there are some differences. The biggest =
might be that, for the most part, private companies can=C2=A0<em>prevent=C2=
=A0</em>trading in their shares. They can make their investors (and employe=
es) sign agreements promising not to sell shares without the company=E2=80=
=99s permission (or without offering them to the company first, etc.). One =
reason for these agreements is that the companies just want to have some co=
ntrol over their stock trading, their shareholder base, etc.=C2=A0Your comp=
any might cheerfully let you sell as much stock as you want to whomever you=
 want, but you have to ask them first; or they might let you sell a lot of =
stock but not to=C2=A0an annoying activist investor; or they might expect y=
ou to be a long-term committed investor and not let you sell too much too f=
ast.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another reason, though, might be stock=C2=A0<e=
m>price=C2=A0</em>management. Big private tech startups are, in part, in th=
e business of giving their investors steadily growing valuations. Everyone =
involved in the startup =E2=80=94=C2=A0the founders, the employees, the ven=
ture capitalists =E2=80=94=C2=A0is betting on it making them rich. If the v=
aluation steadily goes up, then that bet looks good. If the valuation goes =
down, then nobody wants the bet anymore; employees with worthless options a=
re disgruntled and leave, and venture capitalists see things going in the w=
rong direction and won=E2=80=99t invest more.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you=E2=80=99re a public company, your stock=
 price goes up and down based on what people are willing to pay for it on t=
he stock exchange; there=E2=80=99s only so much you can do about it. If you=
=E2=80=99re a private company, (1) your stock price goes up each time you d=
o a fundraising round at a higher valuation, (2) your stock price=C2=A0does=
=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>go down if you do a fundraising round at a lower va=
luation, because you try very hard not to do that, and you=C2=A0<a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34110962.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMDQvcHJpdmF0ZS1tYXJr=
ZXRzLWRvbi10LWxpa2UtdG8tZ28tZG93bj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTI0MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMjQmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB606f17a1" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">use =
=E2=80=9Cstructure=E2=80=9D if you must</a> to avoid a lower price, and (3)=
 your stock doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>to trade in the seconda=
ry market at all. If people want to buy your stock at a higher price than y=
our last fundraising round, sure, why not, you can let them; that=E2=80=99s=
 a good print for your valuation. If people want to buy your stock at a=C2=
=A0<em>lower=C2=A0</em>price than your last fundraising round (and others w=
ant to sell at that price), you can stop them. You don=E2=80=99t ever=C2=A0=
<em>need </em>to have=C2=A0a bad print.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You can just decide that the stock can only trade at a higher pri=
ce than the previous price; if no one wants to trade at a higher price, no =
one can trade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so as startup valuations were going up, pr=
ivate markets looked like the new public markets: People wanted to trade at=
 higher prices, and companies let them. When valuations go down, though, th=
ings change.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is too oversimplified, but it is also kin=
d of true. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34110962.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMjQvc3RhcnR1cC1mb3VuZGVycy1naG9zdC1pbnZlc3RvcnMtdG8tYXZva=
WQtZHJlYWRlZC1kb3duLXJvdW5kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjQyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRp=
