00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 report from Moody=E2=80=99s about shell companies</a>. =E2=80=9CShell comp=
any=E2=80=9D is a somewhat vague term, referring to =E2=80=9Ccorporations w=
ithout significant business assets or operations,=E2=80=9D in Moody=E2=80=
=99s words. There is in general nothing particularly nefarious about having=
 some spare corporations lying around, to optimize liability or ownership o=
r debt subordination or jurisdiction or, yes, fine, of course, taxes. (When=
 I was a young mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer I would occasionally form a =
bunch of Delaware=C2=A0shell companies for future use doing mergers, and I =
always got a tiny Bond-villainish thrill from putting my name on them.) But=
, says Moody=E2=80=99s, =E2=80=9Cthese legal instruments can be abused by b=
ad actors to launder money gained through illicit activities, such as traff=
icking and environmental crime. They can create a mask for sanctioned indiv=
iduals to disguise their business ownership, and they can hide financial cr=
imes, such as tax evasion, fraud, and bribery.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Moody=E2=80=99s analyzed a database of =E2=
=80=9Cmore than 472 million companies=E2=80=9D to identify red flags for wh=
en a company might be a=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>shell company, or a shell co=
mpany anyway?=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moody=E2=80=99s industry practitio=
ners say that a company that raises two or more flags may be at a heightene=
d risk of being a shell company, that is to say, a corporation without acti=
ve business operations or significant assets.=C2=A0The indication that an e=
ntity is a shell company gives customers the ability to further investigate=
 whether the company is potentially being used for illicit activities.</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Red flags include =E2=80=9Cmass registration=
=E2=80=9D (if someone forms 100 companies on the same day, they=E2=80=99re =
probably shells), =E2=80=9Cjurisdictional risk=E2=80=9D (Panama), =E2=80=9C=
financial anomalies=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9Ca China-based textiles and clothing =
manufacturer reported more than $2 billion in revenue in 2019 =E2=80=94 and=
 only one employee=E2=80=9D), =E2=80=9Cdormancy,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccircular=
 ownership=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0=E2=80=9Catypical directorships=E2=80=9D (too =
many directors at a company, or one director being on too many boards).=C2=
=A0And: =E2=80=9CBy sector, the business services sector raises the most fl=
ags with approximately 3.6 million total,=E2=80=9D which sounds right; if y=
ou=E2=80=99re going to set up a fake company it will probably be in the =E2=
=80=9Cbusiness services=E2=80=9D sector rather than, like, biotech. (=E2=80=
=9CWholesale=E2=80=9D comes in second.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the best red flag is director age. Directo=
rs of big public companies tend to be serious professionals chosen for thei=
r expertise and judgment, but directors of shell companies are often warm b=
odies chosen for their willingness to sign their names to=C2=A0documents. (=
Again, as a young mergers-and-acquisitions lawyer, I probably made myself a=
 director of a few merger subs.) Directors of=C2=A0<em>shady=C2=A0</em>shel=
l companies, then, have some propensity to be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0cold bodies? P=
eople who signed fake names to documents?=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The average age of registered company director=
s in Moody=E2=80=99s database is 52 years. A director is typically appointe=
d by the company=E2=80=99s shareholders or board of directors, and their na=
me is listed on the public register of the company. In many jurisdictions, =
minors under the age of 18 aren=E2=80=99t eligible to be directors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moody=E2=80=99s tool has revealed thousands of=
 directors who are as young as zero or older than the world=E2=80=99s longe=
st-living person on record. One listed director =E2=80=94 at 943 years old =
=E2=80=94 would have been born in the 11th century. This director is allege=
dly a minority shareholder and beneficial owner of a Belgium-based business=
 services firm that incorporated in 2018.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Har har har but also there are allegedly more =
than 30,000 shell company directors who are older than 100? Seems high.</p>
